{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98b75709-0b93-4bed-83bf-ad0b2622ccf7","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but I can answer from general knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash reports** — macOS automatically generates crash logs in:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n   These are text-based reports with stack traces, register state, and memory info.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** via the system:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check if SIP blocks core dumps** — System Integrity Protection may prevent core file generation. Verify with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n   If enabled, you may need to boot into Recovery Mode to disable it (not recommended for production).\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **Use `log show`** to get additional crash context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourApp\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, the Apple crash report and `lldb` with the native binary are your primary tools. Ensure you publish with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false` or keep the `.dSYM` bundle) so stack traces are meaningful.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5fd8a76f-90bb-4d65-b447-32f2bca9180d","outputTokens":377},"id":"d25c9538-5a03-40ac-abb5-3bddb6fd5363","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:57:08.979Z","parentId":"82d3e7bc-a609-4af3-a994-f143c4e6f4a8"}
{"type":"assistant.turn_end","data":{"turnId":"1"},"id":"80e51c2d-98cb-42dd-86f4-f823d63221ff","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:57:08.980Z","parentId":"d25c9538-5a03-40ac-abb5-3bddb6fd5363"}
